Writing Guild Emotes For Rooms And Channels
============================================

Guild emotes should use EMOTE_D's guild-scoped emote infrastructure when they
are ordinary social actions. That gives them the same room, targeting,
perspective, channel, preview, search, and random-emote support as global
emotes while restricting use to active members of one guild.

Do not implement an ordinary guild social as a command under
/cmds/guilds/<guild>/emotes/. A standalone command can still be appropriate
when the action moves characters, changes game state, or performs other
complex behavior, but the generic channel-emote parser cannot invoke it.


Static Guild Emotes
===================

Most guild emotes need no LPC object. Register each supported rule directly:

  addemote -guild Mage motion LIV
  New message: $N $vmotion to $t to stand still -- toys are coming!

The addemote preview shows the actor, target, and room perspectives before the
definition is accepted. Repeat the command for each additional rule.

The guild argument is matched case-insensitively against GUILD_NAMES. The
emote name is lower-cased and may contain letters, numbers, underscores, and
hyphens, but must start with a letter. New guild-emote names cannot collide
with global emotes, another guild's emotes, or available commands.


Variable Guild Emotes
=====================

Use a variable emote only when get_emote() must calculate the Message String.
Place the object in the guild's lower-case directory under /cmds/soul/:

  /cmds/soul/mage/motion.c

  string get_emote(string sArg, object *aoWho) {
    if (sArg == "LIV")
      return "$N $vmotion to $t to stand still -- toys are coming!\n";
    return "";
  }

Register the scoped rule, then use a guild redirect as its Message String:

  addemote -guild Mage motion LIV
  New message: ->Guild_Mage_motion

The guild token in the redirect must match the configured guild name. The
object name follows the final underscore and resolves beneath the guild's
directory in /cmds/soul/.


Inspection And Removal
======================

  showemote -guild Mage motion
  rmemote -guild Mage motion LIV
  rmemote -guild Mage motion

The first removal deletes one rule. The second deletes the entire guild emote.
Omitting -guild inspects or changes a global definition instead.


Player Discovery And Access
===========================

Players can use:

  feelings guild [<guild>] [<prefix>]
  semote <emote>
  emoteapropos guild [<guild>] <text>
  random [<player>]

Guild-channel commands that support colon souls can invoke the same emotes,
for example "samchat :jackin". Access is checked every time: leaving the guild
or marking that guild inactive immediately removes access. Players cannot list
or preview definitions belonging to inaccessible guilds.


Persistence
===========

Guild definitions are saved with EMOTE_D in /secure/savedir/soul and survive
daemon reloads and game restarts. That runtime save is environment-local, so
add or migrate the definitions separately in each environment where they are
required.

See also: help guild emotes, help addemote, help showemote, help rmemote
